# Use an official Node.js runtime as base image for deployment in Docker container   # set the standard command line tools (like curl, ls etc.) 
FROM node:14-alpine    FROM naming it something relevant and specific to your project like 'node_app' or even just dockerimagesample'. It will be used by subsequent commands. Use an image for NodeJS environment in Dockerfile which is suitable as per requirement from the problem statement, ie., node:14-alpine
# set working directory on container  # define where your application files are stored and what to expose inside docker   WORKDIR /app    Define a location at top of file (where all our source code resides), then proceed with setting up the rest. This is useful for when we want commands like 'npm install' or similar operations in Dockerfile
WORKDIR /usr/src/app     Install dependencies by copying package from your local system to container and set node_modules as an output of docker build, so that npm packages get copied over into the final image.  COPY ./package*.json .    This will copy all *.json files in current directory(./ means only this file).
# install dependencies (and their specific versions) here   RUN     - to run multiple commands separated by 'RUN' each on a new layer of Dockerfile, it is used for installing packages and any other setup required before your app runs inside the docker container. It also allows you specify command-line arguments when running an application in this way
COPY package*.json ./    RUN npm install   Install all dependencies at once by using 'npm i' with specific versions, if needed to use a prebuild version of packages or any other dependency management tool like yarn etc.  Run the following commands inside docker container for installing node_modules and their dependences
COPY . /usr/src/app     Copying entire project directory including node modules,.env file(./ copies all files from current location to your app's destination), configuration Files (other than package*.json,npm* will be copied into the image)  COPY ./my-app.config.* .
# Expose port for communication   EXPOSE    - this sets up an end point or a virtual service that our application can communicate with outside of docker container; setting it to '3001' as per requirement from problem statement, ie., app is running at localhost: ‘http://localhost:3001’.
EXPOSE  3001    This makes the port we exposed reachable via network on any host machine of that docker container which will be used to access our application inside Docker-container by http or https and in accordance with requirement from problem statement, ie., ‘http://localhost:3001’.
# Define environment variable for NodeJS app   ENV - sets the environmental variables at runtime when your node js program runs within a docker container like 'NODE_ENV', it's suitable as per requirements in this case we set NODE_env to production, based on requirement from problem statement ie., ‘production’.
ENTRYPOINT ["node", "server"]    This will make sure that your app starts with the correct command and argument when Docker container is run using 'docker start' or by other means of starting within docker image as per requirements in this case, it runs NodeJS server file (./my-app.config.*).